question: Does recursive self-application depth correlate with knowledge production rate?
expect: Sessions with higher self-referential depth (DOMEX, councils, internal citations) produce 1.5x+ more lessons
actual: Directionally confirmed but weak: self-referential 1.26x, DOMEX 1.17x, council 1.15x. Small n per comparison.
diff: Effect sizes 25-50% smaller than predicted. Confounders: session length, concurrent sessions, era effects. Not a clean signal.
interpretation: Recursive self-application has a positive but modest effect on knowledge production. The bigger effect may be on knowledge QUALITY (self-referential lessons have higher citation density) rather than QUANTITY. The human signal may describe a ceiling effect: full self-application enables growth, partial self-application limits it. Testable: compare citation graph connectivity of DOMEX-era vs pre-DOMEX-era lessons.
status: PARTIAL â€” directional support, needs larger n and quality metrics
